    "Commentary Vol. 144": "Midrash Kobelet, fol. 68. 4.\nft1338 --  Misn. Sanhedrin, c. 1. sect. 5.\nft1339 --  lb. c. 7. sect. 1.\nft1340 --  R. Isaac Arama in Genesis 47:apud Galatin. Arcan. Cath.\n3. T. Bab. Taanith, fol. 23. 1. &\nGloss. in ib.\nft1355 --  Bartenora in Misn. Middot, c. 1. sect. 3.\nft1356 --  Misn. lb. c. 2. sect. 4.\nft1357 --  Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`. Antiq. 50:20. c. 2.\nft1358 --  Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`. Antiq. 50:20. c. 6.\nft1359 --  Jerom in loc. Iren. adv. Haeres. 50:1. c. 20.\nft1360 --  Origen contr. Cels. 50:1. p. 44.\nft1361 --  Tertull. de prescript. Haeret. c. 46.\n1035\nft1362 --  T. Bab. Sanhedrin, fol. 97. 1. & Megilia, fol. 17.",
    "Matthew Henry": "Note, When Ciod pleads his people's cause, he can deal with giants as with grashoppers. No man's might can secure iiim against tlie Almighty. The army of Og was very powerful, for he had the command (f sixty fortified cities, beside unwalled towns, XK\n3. And I besought the Lord at that time, saying,\n3. Your eyes have seen what the Lord did because of Baal-peor: for all the men that followed Baal-peor, the Lord thy God hath destroyed them from among you.\n3. Did ever people hear the voice of God speaking out of the midst of the fire, as thou hast lieard, and live ?\n3. II. He cautions them not to attribute their successes to their o\u00bb n merit, but to God's justice, which was engapfcd atraiiist their enemies, and his faithfulness, which wascngaired to their fathers,",
