  "9": {
    "Matthew Henry": "Only take heed to thyself, and keep thy soul diligently, lest thou forget the things which thine eyes have seen, and lest they depart from thy heart all the days of thy life; but teach them thy sons, and thy sons' sons;\nv. 9.) Orily take heed to thyself, and keep thy soul diligently, and {y. 15.) Take ye therefore good heed unto yourselves: DEUTERONOMY, IV. and again, {",
    "Walter Brueggemann, Warren Carter": "Pilate and Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`: Roman Justice All Washed Up\n[v_Mat_27_11] [v_Mat_27_12] [v_Mat_27_13] [v_Mat_27_14] [v_Mat_27_15] [v_Mat_27_16] [v_Mat_27_17] [v_Mat_27_18] [v_Mat_27_19] [v_Mat_27_20] [v_Mat_27_21] [v_Mat_27_22] [v_Mat_27_23] [v_Mat_27_24] [v_Mat_27_25] [v_Mat_27_26] (Matt 27:11-26)\nConclusion\n169\nNotes\n181\nBibliography\n221\nSelective General Index\n243\nAuthor Index\n245\nv\nIntroduction\nI\nN THIS STUDY I will explore the relationship between Matthew's Gospel\nand the Roman Empire. I will argue that Matthew's Gospel contests and\nresists the Roman Empire's claims to sovereignty over the world. It sustains\nan alternative community of disciples of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` in anticipation of the coming\ntriumph of God's Empire over all things, including the destruction of Rome's\nempire.\n1 That is to say, the Gospel resists Rome with a social challenge\nin\noffering a vastly different vision and experience of human community, and\nwith a theological\nchallenge in asserting that the world belongs to God not\nRome, and that God's purposes run through Israel and Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, not Rome.\nThis approach to Matthew's Gospel is not the standard one,"
  },
